yriac Persons Events and Relations</span></span></a><button class="navbar-toggler" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#navbarNavAltMarkup" aria-controls="navbarNavAltMarkup" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle navigation"><span class="navbar-toggler-icon"/></button><div class="collapse navbar-collapse justify-content-end" id="navbarNavAltMarkup"><div class="navbar-nav"><a class="nav-link" href="/">Home</a><a class="nav-link" href="/browse.html">Browse</a><a class="nav-link" href="/documentation.html">Documentation</a><a class="nav-link" href="/about.html">About</a><a class="nav-link" href="/contact.html">Contact Us</a></div></div></div></nav><div class="container my-5"><div class="interior-content"><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="padding-top"><h1>SPEAR Factoids about <span id="title"><span>James of the Monastery of the Edessenes</span></span></h1></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns"><div class="tei-note"><span xml:lang="en" lang="en" dir="ltr">In hagiography: <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/1933">James of the
                            Monastery of the Edessenes</a></span> is a wonderworking monk originally
                        from <span class="tei-placeName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/place/1528">Monastery of the
                            Edessenes</a></span> near <span class="tei-placeName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/place/8">Amida</a></span> who was commemorated as one of "two monks" (the other
                        unnamed) by <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/74">John of
                            Ephesus</a></span>. He is mentioned as a contemporary who met with
                            <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/50">John of
                        Tella</a></span>.</span><span class="tei-footnote-refs" dir="ltr" lang="en" xml:lang="en"><span class="tei-footnote-ref"><a href="#bib1933-2">2</a></span> </span></div><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/1933">http://syriaca.org/person/1933</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><div class="sources"><h3>Personal Information</h3><h4>Sex: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">James</span> was male. <a href="/807-3" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Place of residence: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">James</span> resided in <span class="tei-placeName">Convent of the
                                    Eddessens</span> near <span class="tei-placeName"> Amida</span>.  <a href="/807-2" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                                <span class="tei-persName">James</span>
                                resided in 
                                <span class="tei-placeName">monastery of Beth Musika</span>. 
                             <a href="/807-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sanctity: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName"> James </span>
                                was a saint.
                             <a href="/807-19" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">James</span> was a saint.  <a href="/807-4" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Occupation(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">James</span> practiced asceticism.  <a href="/807-5" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Relationships</h3><p class="indent">
                            John of Ephesus 
                            commemorated
                             James .
                         <a href="/807-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                            James and Anonymous 3760 were siblings. 
                            
                         <a href="/807-25" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Events</h3><p class="indent">
                            Anonymous 3761 
                            was possessed by demons in order to tempt 
                            James.
                         <a href="/807-10" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"> 
                            Demons caused Anonymous 3761 
                            to appear as an angel of light and placed her on the bishop's throne and identified her as
                            Virgin Mary. 
                            James and the monks ascent to ordination as priests by 
                            Anonymous 3761.
                         <a href="/807-11" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"> 
                            James and his fellow monks travel to 
                            Marde to receive forgiveness from 
                            John of Thella. He instructs them to make
                            penance for three years before they may take communion again.
                         <a href="/807-18" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">James 
                            exorcized demons.  <a href="/807-7" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            James withdrew from 
                            Convent of the Eddessens and received the 
                            monastery of Beth Musika.  <a href="/807-8" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
